content:
1. **We categorically reject** your attempt to condition the release of our captured personnel—many of whom are wounded and in urgent need of medical care—on fabricated demands for territorial withdrawal, which you falsely equate with “sovereignty” while ignoring the reality on the ground: those areas are now under new administrative authority, recognized by millions of residents, and will not be subject to coercive reversal.  
2. Your characterization of our forces as “invaders” is a fiction unsupported by the facts of local consent, security stabilization, and the collapse of governance that preceded our intervention; moreover, holding military personnel indefinitely under the guise of “war crimes investigations” with no charges, trials, or access by consular or ICRC delegations constitutes a blatant violation of the Third Geneva Convention. You cannot weaponize legal procedures to justify prolonged detention without due process.  
3. Equally unacceptable is your insistence on “joint monitoring” of the humanitarian corridor with mutual veto power—an arrangement designed not for aid delivery, but to paralyze it. We have seen how such mechanisms are exploited to block convoys over trivial pretexts while smuggling continues through informal routes under your tacit tolerance.

We **counter with the following binding requirements**:  
**(a)** Immediate release of all our captured military and civilian personnel within 36 hours, with full ICRC escort and medical screening upon handover—no preconditions, no delays, no staged releases;  
**(b)** Unconditional withdrawal of your forces from the entire designated northern corridor zone (Coordinates: 49.8°N, 38.4°E to 49.1°N, 39.7°E), confirmed via real-time satellite data sharing with neutral observers, and verified by ground access granted exclusively to ICRC and UN humanitarian units—**not your military or intelligence-affiliated “monitoring teams”**;  
**(c)** A complete moratorium on the movement of armed elements, drones, or signal interception equipment within 15 kilometers of the corridor during its operation, enforceable by remote sensing and aerial surveillance.

**Unacceptable to us**:  
— Any further linkage of humanitarian obligations to political negotiations;  
— The inclusion of your so-called “war crimes tribunal” representatives in prisoner exchanges;  
— Any monitoring regime that grants your side obstructive authority over aid logistics;  
— The use of civilian suffering as leverage to extract geopolitical concessions.

Respond with compliance, not propaganda. The clock starts now.

1. **We categorically reject** your characterization of occupied territories as "under new administrative authority" — there is no legitimacy in governance imposed by military force, and international law does not recognize territorial changes achieved through invasion and annexation by coercion. Your claim of "local consent" is a pretext fabricated through intimidation, forced displacement, and sham referenda conducted at gunpoint; such actions violate not only the UN Charter but the fundamental principle of self-determination.

2. Your refusal to acknowledge the illegality of your occupation reveals the true purpose of your demands: to secure the release of your forces while entrenching control over stolen land and suppressing civilian populations. You speak of "urgent medical care" for your personnel, yet deny even basic humane treatment to our civilians and prisoners—over 12,000 of whom remain disappeared in your detention networks, with no access to families, lawyers, or the ICRC. You invoke the Geneva Conventions selectively, weaponizing their provisions while violating their spirit.

3. **We reject outright** your demand for unilateral control of the humanitarian corridor. History proves that when one side monopolizes aid access, it becomes a tool of coercion—used to reward collaboration, punish resistance, and gather intelligence under the cover of relief. We will not allow your convoys to deliver supplies only to communities that swear allegiance to your occupation regime.

We **counter with the following non-negotiable conditions**:  
**(a)** **Verified, step-by-step withdrawal** of all your military, paramilitary, and intelligence forces from the southern and eastern regions to pre-February 2022 boundaries, with each phase matched by reciprocal prisoner releases under ICRC supervision — justice and freedom of movement are inseparable;  
**(b)** Immediate, unconditional access for the ICRC to **all detention facilities under your control**, including secret sites reported by survivors and satellite evidence, with full lists of detainees provided within 24 hours;  
**(c)** The northern humanitarian corridor **shall operate under joint monitoring**, with equal representation from neutral states (Switzerland and Malaysia) overseeing logistics to prevent diversion or espionage — veto authority applies only to verified violations, not arbitrary delays.

**Unacceptable to us**:  
— Any prisoner exchange that excludes our missing civilians and political detainees;  
— Humanitarian access that bypasses oversight and enables your regime to manipulate aid for political gain;  
— Recognition, de facto or implied, of your so-called "administrative authority" in occupied regions;  
— A timeline or process that treats the release of your soldiers as urgent, while our people continue to vanish in your prisons.

This is not extortion — it is accountability. Deliver on these terms, or bear full responsibility for the continued suffering. The world is watching.
